  "doc_id": "59116",
  "text": "In this regard Tollip resembles the negative regulators MyD88s and IRAK-M, which also bind to IRAK-1 and halt signaling by blocking recruitment of IRAK-4 and thereby the phosphorylation and/or activation of IRAK-1 (4, 7). IRAK-Mnull mice have been generated showing that IRAK-M is important for suppression of IL-1␤ and various TLR ligands [CITATION_1] . This suggests that Tollip (or MyD88s) does not act interchangeably with IRAK-M but that Tollip may function as a suppressor in a cooperative manner and/or in specific cellular contexts (i.e., specific cell types or under specific conditions of stimulation). Unlike IRAK-M/MyD88s or indeed many other inflammation suppressors (reference 18 and references therein), Tollip is constitutively expressed [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Its presence in unstimulated cells, together with several newly identified binding partners (discussed below) also suggests the possibility that Tollip's function is of a more multifaceted nature. To examine these possibilities, we generated Tollip-deficient mice by gene-targeting. Here we report the initial characterization of Tollip-deficient cells and mice and, importantly, that Tollip deficiency results in attenuated responses to the proinflammatory cytokines, IL-6 and tumor necrosis factor alpha (TNF-␣).",
